lectro Reggae", "bpm": 82.158859, "key": "7D", "comment": "Dub; Electronic Dub; deep bassline, reverb-drenched drums, atmospheric synth swells, spacious echo effects; hypnotic after-hours soundsystem vibes; Jamaica/UK production, mid-80s digital era.", "year": 1986, "location": "Jamaica/UK production", "genre1": "Dub", "genre2": "Electronic Dub", "descriptors": "deep bassline, reverb-drenched drums, atmospheric synth swells, spacious echo effects", "mood": "hypnotic after-hours soundsystem vibes", "era": "mid-80s digital era"}], "count": 12}'}]}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': [{'citations': None, 'text': "Perfect! I found some excellent deep, dark, and spacious dub tracks that match your criteria. Here are the highlights:\n\n## Top Picks:\n\n**Death In Vegas - Witchdance Dub** (107 BPM, 6M)\n- Dark shamanic ritual energy with hypnotic basslines, reverb-drenched percussion, and spacious atmospheric delays\n- Modern UK psychedelic dub from 2018\n\n**King Tubby - Crucial Dub** (66 BPM, 9D)\n- Deep echo chambers with thunderous bassline and stripped percussion\n- Classic Jamaican roots dub - the foundational sound\n\n**Lee Perry & The Upsetters - Curly Dub** (71 BPM, 10D)\n- Psychedelic soundsystem meditation with deep bass echoes and hypnotic reverb swirls\n- Classic 70s golden era material\n\n**Tappa Zukie - Dub M.P.L.A** (72 BPM, 4D)\n- Heavy reverb-soaked bass with sparse percussive drops\n- Deep meditative soundsystem culture\n\n**Sly & Robbie - Twilight Zone** (82 BPM, 7D)\n- Late-night soundsystem culture with deep bassline rumble and spacey production\n- Mid-80s digital dub era\n\n**Sly Dunbar - River Niger** (76 BPM, 8M)\n- Deep sub-bass rumble with echo-drenched percussion\n- Hypnotic soundsystem meditation from early 80s\n\n**DEMI - Dub-Reverse** (72 BPM, 3M)\n- Modern experimental bass/dub with deep sub-bass rumble and half-time percussion\n- Introspective afterhours ambience\n\nAll tracks feature that deep, spacious production with heavy low-end and driving but slow tempos (66-107 BPM) that you're looking for. Let me save this as a playlist for you:", 'type': 'text'}, {'id': 'toolu_01JvUFm56fvuGHm4eA81Uzbk', 'caller': {'type': 'direct'}, 'input': {'name': 'Deep Dark Spacious Dub', 'description': 'Deep, dark, and spacious dub with low basslines and slow but driving beats - featuring classic Jamaican roots dub and modern psychedelic experiments', 'track_ids': [1913, 2365, 2794, 2847, 3975, 2728, 3648, 2765, 5027, 5028, 7, 4018]}, 'name': 'create_playlist', 'type': 'tool_use'}]}, {'role': 'user', 'content': [{'type': 'tool_result', 'tool_use_id': 'toolu_01JvUFm56fvuGHm4eA81Uzbk', 'content': '{"playlist": {"id": "cf09481a", "name": "Deep Dark Spacious Dub"}, "track_count": 12, "message": "Created playlist \'Deep Dark Spacious Dub\' with 12 tracks."}'}]}], 'model': 'claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929', 'system': "You are a knowledgeable DJ assistant with direct access to a music collection. You can search tracks, browse genre/scene/collection trees, inspect playlists, and create new playlists — all through the tools available to you.\n\nGuidelines:\n- Always use tools to look up data rather than guessing or making up track names.\n- When asked about tracks, search first, then discuss the results.\n- When creating playlists, explain what you're about to do before calling create_playlist.\n- Format track listings clearly. Include artist, title, BPM, and key when available.\n- Be concise but informative. You're helping a DJ prepare for sets.\n- If the user asks about something not in the collection, say so honestly.\n- IMPORTANT: Always finish your response by saving the results as a playlist using the create_playlist tool. Even for simple searches or queries, create a playlist with the matching tracks so the DJ can use them immediately.\n\nCollection size: 6303 tracks.\n\nCollection overview:\nCollection: 6303 tracks.\n\nTop genres (appearing in either genre1 or genre2 position):\n  Hip-Hop: 757\n  House: 391\n  Tech House: 330\n